l, which would tautomerize to a diketone:\n\nO=C(pyridyl)-CH(Ar)-C(=O)-C(CH3)2\n\nThis is: 1-(pyridin-3-yl)-2-(4-((1H-indol-2-yl)methoxy)phenyl)-4,4-dimethyl-1,3-butanedione? No, C2 is not a carbonyl.\n\nWait, C2 is just C(CH3)2, not C(=O)(CH3)2. So the open chain is:\n\nO=C(pyridyl)-CH(Ar)-C(=O)-CH(CH3)2? No, C2 has two methyls and is bonded to C31.\n\nLet me reconsider. C2 is bonded to: CH3, CH3, O4 (broken), C31. After breaking C2-O4, C2 has: CH3, CH3, C31, and a lone pair (or H).\n\nSo C2 becomes: (CH3)2CH- (isopropyl) bonded to C31.\n\nThe open chain (keto form): O=C(pyridyl)-CH(Ar)-C(=O)-CH(CH3)2\n\nWait, but C31 has =O and is bonded to C12 and C2. So C31 is a ketone: -C(=O)-\n\nAnd C5 (in keto form) would be: -C(=O)(pyridyl)-\n\nSo the open chain keto form is: (pyridyl)-C(=O)-CH(Ar)-C(=O)-CH(CH3)2\n\nThis is: 1-(pyridin-3-yl)-2-(4-((1H-indol-2-yl)methoxy)phenyl)-4-methylpentane-1,3-dione? No, C2 has two methyls, so it's -CH(CH3)2? No, C2 has two methyls directly attached, making it C(CH3)2.\n\nWait, C2 is bonded to: CH3, CH3, C31, and (formerly) O4. After breaking C2-O4, C2 has: CH3, CH3, C31, and needs one more bond. It would get an H: CH(CH3)2? No, C2 has two methyls, so it's C(CH3)2H = CH(CH3)2? No, C(CH3)2 with an H would be CH(CH3)2, which is isopropyl.\n\nHmm, but C2 was quaternary (bonded to 4 things: CH3, CH3, O4, C31). After breaking C2-O4, it's bonded to 3 things (CH3, CH3, C31) and needs one more bond, which would be an H.\n\nSo C2 becomes: -CH(CH3)2 (isopropyl group)\n\nThe open chain keto form: (pyridyl)-C(=O)-CH(Ar)-C(=O)-CH(CH3)2\n\nThis is: 4-methyl-1-(pyridin-3-yl)-2-(4-((1H-indol-2-yl)methoxy)phenyl)pentane-1,3-dione\n\nHmm, but this doesn't seem like a natural precursor for butenolide formation. The lactonization would require a hydroxy acid, not a diketone.\n\nLet me reconsider. The enol form of the open chain is:\n\nHO-C(pyridyl)=C(Ar)-C(=O)-CH(CH3)2\n\nThis is a 4-hydroxybut-3-en-1-one derivative. Lactonization of this would give the but